n for Men?:  Strange Silence and Strange Bedfellows in the Public Debate Over Discrimination Against Women in College Admissions], Engage (November 2011).\n* {{Cite journal | last = Pollak | first = Oliver B. | title = Antisemitism, the Harvard Plan, and the roots of reverse discrimination | journal = Jewish Social Studies | volume = 45 | issue = 2 | pages = 113\u201322 | date = 1983 | jstor = 4467214 | ref = none }}\n* {{cite book | last = Vieth-Entus | first = Susanne | title = Sozialquote: Berliner Gymnasien sollen mehr Sch\u00fcler aus armen Familien aufnehmen | date = 29 December 2008 }} Der Tagesspiegel\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cite SEP |url-id=affirmative-action |title=Affirmative Action}}\n* {{NYTtopic|subjects/a/affirmative_action}}\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/affirm/affirm.htm Affirmative Action] collected news and commentary at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* [https://www.pbs.org/now/shows/434/index.html Does the success of Barack Obama mean we no longer need affirmative action?] NOW on PBS investigates\n* [http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160518092243/http://cle.ens-lsh.fr/29902590/0/fiche___pagelibre/&RH=CDL_ANG020000 An interview with Professor Randall Kennedy about the presidency of Barack Obama and affirmative action] Clifford Armion for La Cl\u00e9 des langues.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070615173751/http://www.minorityrights.org/admin/Download/pdf/MRG_RomaBriefing2006.pdf Substantive Equality, Positive Action and Roma Rights in the European Union], Report by Minority Rights Group International\n* [[Intelligence Squared]] debate: [http://intelligencesquaredus.org/debates/past-debates/item/1054-affirmative-action-on-campus-does-more-harm-than-good Affirmative Action on Campus Does More Harm than Good]\n\n{{Employment}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Affirmative Action}}\n[[Category:Affirmative action| ]]\n[[Category:Discrimination]]\n[[Category:Prejudice and discrimination]]\n[[Category:Race and law]]\n[[Category:Majority\u2013minority relations]]\n", "name_user": "H.Afrin", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a line", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Affirmative_action"}
{"title_page": "Voineasa, V\u00e2lcea", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = V\u00e2lcea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in V\u00e2lcea County\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|25|N|23|57|E|type:city_source:kolossus-itwiki|display=it}}\n|name=Voineasa\n|image_skyline=Voineasa, Romania - panoramio (2).jpg\n|image_caption=Ski slope in Voineasa\n|image_map              = Voineasa en distrikto V\u00e2lcea.png\n}}\n'''Voineasa''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[V\u00e2lcea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of three villages: Valea M\u0103ce\u0219ului, Voineasa and Voine\u0219i\u021ba.\n\nSituated on the valley of the [[Lotru River]], the commune is also a spa resort, with a Communist-era hotel dominating the locality, as well as several other tourist facilities. 25 km upstream of the valley is [[Vidra Lake]], one of the largest dams and reservoirs in Romania, built between 1965 and 1972, and also the newly built Transalpina ski resort on lake's shore (Transalpina Resort is not on [[Transalpina Road]] but is connected to it by road).\n\n{{Spa towns in Romania}}\n{{LocalitiesValcea}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{commonscat}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voineasa, Valcea}}\n[[Category:Communes in V\u00e2lcea County]]\n[[Category:Spa towns in Romania]]\n\n{{V\u00e2lcea-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = V\u00e2lcea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in V\u00e2lcea County\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|25|N|23|57|E|type:city_source:kolossus-itwiki|display=it}}\n|name=Voineasa\n|image_skyline=Voineasa, Romania - panoramio (2).jpg\n|image_caption=Ski slope in Voineasa\n|image_map=\n}}\n'''Voineasa''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[V\u00e2lcea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of three villages: Valea M\u0103ce\u0219ului, Voineasa and Voine\u0219i\u021ba.\n\nSituated on the valley of the [[Lotru River]], the commune is also a spa resort, with a Communist-era hotel dominating the locality, as well as several other tourist facilities. 25 km upstream of the valley is [[Vidra Lake]], one of the largest dams and reservoirs in Romania, built between 1965 and 1972, and also the newly built Transalpina ski resort on lake's shore (Transalpina Resort is not on [[Transalpina Road]] but is connected to it by road).\n\n{{Spa towns in Romania}}\n{{LocalitiesValcea}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{commonscat}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voineasa, Valcea}}\n[[Category:Communes in V\u00e2lcea County]]\n[[Category:Spa towns in Romania]]\n\n{{V\u00e2lcea-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voineasa,_V%C3%A2lcea"}
{"title_page": "Suzette Davenport", "text_new": "{{Short description|Retired chief constable}}\n'''Suzette Louise Davenport''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|QPM}} (born January 1963) is the former [[chief constable]] of [[Gloucestershire Constabulary]]. She was appointed in 2013, becoming the first woman to serve in the role; prior to this, she had held various other policing roles.  She retired in 2017, having served thirty years as a police officer.\n\n==Life and career==\nSuzette Louise Davenport was born in January 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/aD_BterVED2BX_YZMOgZP9Lle4c/appointments|title=Suzette Louise Davenport|website=[[Companies House]]|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>  Though Davenport is from North Yorkshire, she started her policing career with [[West Mercia Police]].<ref name=BBC/>  She went on to work in several police roles for different forces;<ref name=PCC>{{cite web|url=https://www.gloucestershire-pcc.gov.uk/countys-first-woman-police-chief-who-smashed-the-glass-ceiling/|title=County\u2019s first woman police chief who smashed the glass ceiling|website=Office of the Police and Crime Commissioner for Gloucestershire|date=30 January 2017|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=BBC>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-38799275|title=Chief constable to retire in April|date=26 December 2017|accessdate=26 December 2017|website=[[BBC News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310201838/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-38799275|archive-date=10 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> by 2002, she was working for [[Staffordshire Police]].<ref name=Gazette>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazetteseries.co.uk/news/14335261.gloucestershire-police-chief-constable-suzette-davenport-cleared-of-misconduct-following-murder-investigation-probe/|work=Gazette|title=Gloucestershire Police chief constable Suzette Davenport cleared of misconduct following murder investigation probe|date=10 March 2016|access-date=1 April 2020|author=<!--staff author-->|publisher=[[Newsquest]]}}</ref><ref name=ES>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/crime/2017/10/04/kevin-nunes-watchdog-report-finds-senior-officers-failed-in-their-duties-but-none-will-be-held-accountable-for-scandal/|title=Kevin Nunes investigation: Watchdog report finds senior officers 'failed in their duties' but none face action|work=[[Express & Star]]|last=Golledge|first=Rob|date=4 October 2017|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212235826/https://www.expressandstar.com/news/crime/2017/10/04/kevin-nunes-watchdog-report-finds-senior-officers-failed-in-their-duties-but-none-will-be-held-accountable-for-scandal/|archive-date=12 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  She moved to work for the [[Home Office]] briefly in 2005; she then returned to Staffordshire Police, to the role of assistant chief constable.<ref name=BBC/>  At one point during her career with the Staffordshire force, she held the \"crime and diversity\" portfolio.<ref name=College>{{cite web|url=http://www.college.police.uk/About/Governance/Board/Pages/davenport.aspx|title=Suzette Davenport - College of Policing|website=[[College of Policing]]|accessdate=26 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227121911/http://www.college.police.uk/About/Governance/Board/Pages/davenport.aspx|archive-date=27 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In 2007, Davenport moved to [[West Midlands Police]], where she was responsible for \"intelligence and neighbourhood policing\".<ref name=PCC/>\n\nIn 2011, while Davenport was deputy chief constable with [[Northamptonshire Police]], the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]] launched an enquiry into the conduct of four Staffordshire officers in 2002, including Davenport, in connection with the murder of amateur footballer, Kevin Nunes.  Five people were convicted of the murder of Nunes in 2008; the convicted individuals lodged an appeal with the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-16311557|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Police chiefs in misconduct probe over Kevin Nunes murder|date=23 December 2011|author=<!--Staff author-->|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129043450/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-16311557|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and their convictions were quashed in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-17304165|title=Kevin Nunes killing: Five cleared at appeal court|work=[[BBC News]]|date=8 March 2012|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222043450/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-17304165|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  The IPCC cleared the officers, including Davenport, of misconduct in 2016;<ref name=EStimeline>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/crime/2016/03/11/kevin-nunes-gangland-murder-painful-wait-for-truths/|title=Police cleared on Kevin Nunes gangland murder probe: Express & Star investigates|author=<!--staff writer-->|work=[[Express & Star]]|date=11 March 2016|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510020425/https://www.expressandstar.com/news/crime/2016/03/11/kevin-nunes-gangland-murder-painful-wait-for-truths/|archive-date=10 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Davenport said she was \"pleased and relieved\" that the case into her had concluded.<ref name=Gazette/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2016/03/11/kevin-nunes-gangland-murder-inquiry-into-police-officers-right-but-costly-says-cleared-staffordshire-police-chief/|title=Kevin Nunes gangland murder: Inquiry into police officers 'right but costly', says cleared Staffordshire Police chief|date=11 March 2016|author=<!--Staff writer-->|access-date=1 April 2020|work=[[Express & Star]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403075829/http://www.expressandstar.com/news/2016/03/11/kevin-nunes-gangland-murder-inquiry-into-police-officers-right-but-costly-says-cleared-staffordshire-police-chief/|archive-date=3 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2013, Davenport was the vice-president of the [[British Association for Women in Policing]] for eight years.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[BBC News]]|author=<!--Staff writer-->|title=Suzette Davenport is Chief Constable of Gloucestershire Police|date=9 January 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-20950754|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128081149/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-20950754|archive-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, she was appointed as the national lead for roads policing for the [[Association of Chief Police Officers]] in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalroadsafetyconference.org.uk/agenda-speakers/suzette-davenport/|website=National Road Safety Conference|title=Suzette Davenport|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> a role she held until retirement.<ref name=BBC/>\n\nIn 2013, she became the first female chief constable of [[Gloucestershire Constabulary]].<ref>{{cite news|work=[[ITV News]]|url=https://www.itv.com/news/westcountry/2013-01-09/gloucestershires-new-police-chief/|title=Gloucestershire's new police chief|date=9 January 2013|access-date=28 March 2020|author=<!--Staff author-->|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815112912/http://www.itv.com/news/westcountry/2013-01-09/gloucestershires-new-police-chief/|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>  As of 2016, Davenport sat on the board of the [[College of Policing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.college.police.uk/News/archive/June_2016/Pages/Queen%E2%80%99s_Birthday_Honours.aspx|website=[[College of Policing]]|title=Queen\u2019s Birthday Honours for College staff|date=June 2016|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104142708/http://www.college.police.uk/News/archive/June_2016/Pages/Queen%E2%80%99s_Birthday_Honours.aspx|archive-date=4 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  While in the role, it was reported that she had banned officers in her force from having beards unless they were covered,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/hairy-police-officers-kick-up-a-right-fuzz-31427828.html|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|title=Hairy police officers kick up a right fuzz|last=McNeilly|first=Claire|date=4 August 2015|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160103121040/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/hairy-police-officers-kick-up-a-right-fuzz-31427828.html|archive-date=3 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> with the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Newsbeat]]'' reporting that beard nets would be permitted as an alternative.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Newsbeat]]|date=27 July 2015|title=Police aren't happy over proposed beard-nets|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/33674959/police-arent-happy-over-proposed-beard-nets|access-date=1 April 2020|author=<!--Staff author-->|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724235124/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/33674959/police-arent-happy-over-proposed-beard-nets|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  Davenport retired in 2017, after thirty years as a police officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gloucestershire.police.uk/news-room/latest-news/chief-constable-suzette-davenport-announces-retirement/|title=Chief Constable Suzette Davenport announces retirement|website=[[Gloucestershire Constabulary]]|accessdate=26 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226234418/https://www.gloucestershire.police.uk/news-room/latest-news/chief-constable-suzette-davenport-announces-retirement/|archive-date=26 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nDavenport was ranked at number 79 in ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 2014 [[Rainbow List]] of influential [[LGBT]] people, having [[come out]] as a lesbian at Pride in Gloucestershire earlier in that year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/therainbowlist/rainbow-list-2014-1-to-100-9848457.html |title=Rainbow List 2014, 1 to 101 |date=9 November 2014 |access-date=29 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503134543/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/therainbowlist/rainbow-list-2014-1-to-100-9848457.html |archive-date=3 May 2015 |url-status=live |work=[[The Independent on Sunday]]}}</ref>   She was awarded the [[Queen's Police Medal]] in 2016,<ref name=BBC/> as well as an [[honorary doctorate]] by the [[University of Gloucestershire]].<ref>{{cite news|work=Gloucester Review|author=<!--Staff author-->|date=8 September 2016|access-date=28 March 2020|url=http://www.gloucesterreview.co.uk/article.cfm?id=102093&headline=Honorary%20doctorate%20for%20chief%20constable&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2016|title=Honorary doctorate for chief constable}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=[[University of Gloucestershire]]|title=Chief Constable receives Honorary Award|date=4 November 2016|url=https://www.glos.ac.uk/news/pages/chief-constable-receives-honorary-award.aspx|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427014546/http://www.glos.ac.uk/news/Pages/chief-constable-receives-honorary-award.aspx|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline|Gloucestershire Constabulary}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davenport, Suzette}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British police officers]]\n[[Category:Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:British women police officers]]\n[[Category:People from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Queen's Police Medal]]\n[[Category:Lesbian police officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Retired chief constable}}\n'''Suzette Louise Davenport''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|QPM}} (born January 1963) is the former [[chief constable]] of [[Gloucestershire Constabulary]]. She was appointed in 2013, becoming the first woman to serve in the role; prior to this, she had held various other policing roles.  She retired in 2017, having served thirty years as a police officer.\n\n==Life and career==\nSuzette Louise Davenport was born in January 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/aD_BterVED2BX_YZMOgZP9Lle4c/appointments|title=Suzette Louise Davenport|website=[[Companies House]]|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>  Though Davenport is from North Yorkshire, she started her policing career with [[West Mercia Police]].<ref name=BBC/>  She went on to work in several police roles for different forces;<ref name=PCC>{{cite web|url=https://www.gloucestershire-pcc.gov.uk/countys-first-woman-police-chief-who-smashed-the-glass-ceiling/|title=County\u2019s first woman police chief who smashed the glass ceiling|website=Office of the Police and Crime Commissioner for Gloucestershire|date=30 January 2017|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=BBC>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-38799275|title=Chief constable to retire in April|date=26 December 2017|accessdate=26 December 2017|website=[[BBC News]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170310201838/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-38799275|archive-date=10 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> by 2002, she was working for [[Staffordshire Police]].<ref name=Gazette>{{cite news|url=https://www.gazetteseries.co.uk/news/14335261.gloucestershire-police-chief-constable-suzette-davenport-cleared-of-misconduct-following-murder-investigation-probe/|work=Gazette|title=Gloucestershire Police chief constable Suzette Davenport cleared of misconduct following murder investigation probe|date=10 March 2016|access-date=1 April 2020|author=<!--staff author-->|publisher=[[Newsquest]]}}</ref><ref name=ES>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/crime/2017/10/04/kevin-nunes-watchdog-report-finds-senior-officers-failed-in-their-duties-but-none-will-be-held-accountable-for-scandal/|title=Kevin Nunes investigation: Watchdog report finds senior officers 'failed in their duties' but none face action|work=[[Express & Star]]|last=Golledge|first=Rob|date=4 October 2017|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212235826/https://www.expressandstar.com/news/crime/2017/10/04/kevin-nunes-watchdog-report-finds-senior-officers-failed-in-their-duties-but-none-will-be-held-accountable-for-scandal/|archive-date=12 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  She moved to work for the [[Home Office]] briefly in 2005; she then returned to Staffordshire Police, to the role of assistant chief constable.<ref name=BBC/>  At one point during her career with the Staffordshire force, she held the \"crime and diversity\" portfolio.<ref name=College>{{cite web|url=http://www.college.police.uk/About/Governance/Board/Pages/davenport.aspx|title=Suzette Davenport - College of Policing|website=[[College of Policing]]|accessdate=26 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171227121911/http://www.college.police.uk/About/Governance/Board/Pages/davenport.aspx|archive-date=27 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In 2007, Davenport moved to [[West Midlands Police]], where she was responsible for \"intelligence and neighbourhood policing\".<ref name=PCC/>\n\nIn 2011, while Davenport was deputy chief constable with [[Northamptonshire Police]], the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]] launched an enquiry into the conduct of four Staffordshire officers in 2002, including Davenport, in connection with the murder of amateur footballer, Kevin Nunes.  Five people were convicted of the murder of Nunes in 2008; the convicted individuals lodged an appeal with the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-16311557|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Police chiefs in misconduct probe over Kevin Nunes murder|date=23 December 2011|author=<!--Staff author-->|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129043450/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-northamptonshire-16311557|archive-date=29 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and their convictions were quashed in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-17304165|title=Kevin Nunes killing: Five cleared at appeal court|work=[[BBC News]]|date=8 March 2012|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222043450/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-17304165|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  The IPCC cleared the officers, including Davenport, of misconduct in 2016;<ref name=EStimeline>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/crime/2016/03/11/kevin-nunes-gangland-murder-painful-wait-for-truths/|title=Police cleared on Kevin Nunes gangland murder probe: Express & Star investigates|author=<!--staff writer-->|work=[[Express & Star]]|date=11 March 2016|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510020425/https://www.expressandstar.com/news/crime/2016/03/11/kevin-nunes-gangland-murder-painful-wait-for-truths/|archive-date=10 May 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Davenport said she was \"pleased and relieved\" that the case into her had concluded.<ref name=Gazette/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/news/2016/03/11/kevin-nunes-gangland-murder-inquiry-into-police-officers-right-but-costly-says-cleared-staffordshire-police-chief/|title=Kevin Nunes gangland murder: Inquiry into police officers 'right but costly', says cleared Staffordshire Police chief|date=11 March 2016|author=<!--Staff writer-->|access-date=1 April 2020|work=[[Express & Star]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403075829/http://www.expressandstar.com/news/2016/03/11/kevin-nunes-gangland-murder-inquiry-into-police-officers-right-but-costly-says-cleared-staffordshire-police-chief/|archive-date=3 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPrior to 2013, Davenport was the vice-president of the [[British Association for Women in Policing]] for eight years.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[BBC News]]|author=<!--Staff writer-->|title=Suzette Davenport is Chief Constable of Gloucestershire Police|date=9 January 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-20950754|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128081149/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-gloucestershire-20950754|archive-date=28 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, she was appointed as the national lead for roads policing for the [[Association of Chief Police Officers]] in 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalroadsafetyconference.org.uk/agenda-speakers/suzette-davenport/|website=National Road Safety Conference|title=Suzette Davenport|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> a role she held until retirement.<ref name=BBC/>\n\nIn 2013, she became the first female chief constable of [[Gloucestershire Constabulary]].<ref>{{cite news|work=[[ITV News]]|url=https://www.itv.com/news/westcountry/2013-01-09/gloucestershires-new-police-chief/|title=Gloucestershire's new police chief|date=9 January 2013|access-date=28 March 2020|author=<!--Staff author-->|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815112912/http://www.itv.com/news/westcountry/2013-01-09/gloucestershires-new-police-chief/|archive-date=15 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>  As of 2016, Davenport sat on the board of the [[College of Policing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.college.police.uk/News/archive/June_2016/Pages/Queen%E2%80%99s_Birthday_Honours.aspx|website=[[College of Policing]]|title=Queen\u2019s Birthday Honours for College staff|date=June 2016|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104142708/http://www.college.police.uk/News/archive/June_2016/Pages/Queen%E2%80%99s_Birthday_Honours.aspx|archive-date=4 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  While in the role, it was reported that she had banned officers in her force from having beards unless they were covered,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/hairy-police-officers-kick-up-a-right-fuzz-31427828.html|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|title=Hairy police officers kick up a right fuzz|last=McNeilly|first=Claire|date=4 August 2015|access-date=1 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160103121040/http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/uk/hairy-police-officers-kick-up-a-right-fuzz-31427828.html|archive-date=3 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> with the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Newsbeat]]'' reporting that beard nets would be permitted as an alternative.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Newsbeat]]|date=27 July 2015|title=Police aren't happy over proposed beard-nets|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/33674959/police-arent-happy-over-proposed-beard-nets|access-date=1 April 2020|author=<!--Staff author-->|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190724235124/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/33674959/police-arent-happy-over-proposed-beard-nets|archive-date=24 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  Davenport retired in 2017, after 30 years as a police officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gloucestershire.police.uk/news-room/latest-news/chief-constable-suzette-davenport-announces-retirement/|title=Chief Constable Suzette Davenport announces retirement|website=[[Gloucestershire Constabulary]]|accessdate=26 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226234418/https://www.gloucestershire.police.uk/news-room/latest-news/chief-constable-suzette-davenport-announces-retirement/|archive-date=26 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\nDavenport was ranked at number 79 in ''[[The Independent on Sunday]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s 2014 [[Rainbow List]] of influential [[LGBT]] people, having [[come out]] as a lesbian at Pride in Gloucestershire earlier in that year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/therainbowlist/rainbow-list-2014-1-to-100-9848457.html |title=Rainbow List 2014, 1 to 101 |date=9 November 2014 |access-date=29 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150503134543/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/therainbowlist/rainbow-list-2014-1-to-100-9848457.html |archive-date=3 May 2015 |url-status=live |work=[[The Independent on Sunday]]}}</ref>   She was awarded the [[Queen's Police Medal]] in 2016,<ref name=BBC/> as well as an [[honorary doctorate]] by the [[University of Gloucestershire]].<ref>{{cite news|work=Gloucester Review|author=<!--Staff author-->|date=8 September 2016|access-date=28 March 2020|url=http://www.gloucesterreview.co.uk/article.cfm?id=102093&headline=Honorary%20doctorate%20for%20chief%20constable&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2016|title=Honorary doctorate for chief constable}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=[[University of Gloucestershire]]|title=Chief Constable receives Honorary Award|date=4 November 2016|url=https://www.glos.ac.uk/news/pages/chief-constable-receives-honorary-award.aspx|access-date=28 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427014546/http://www.glos.ac.uk/news/Pages/chief-constable-receives-honorary-award.aspx|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline|Gloucestershire Constabulary}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davenport, Suzette}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British police officers]]\n[[Category:Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:British women police officers]]\n[[Category:People from Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Queen's Police Medal]]\n[[Category:Lesbian police officers]]\n", "name_user": "YorkshireLad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career:ce (internal consistency)", "url_page": "//en.